{"title_page": "Hopin Academy", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Hopin Academy \n| type = for-profit [[private company]]\n| genre = private educational organization in the developing world\n| founders = MacCarthy M. Mac-Gbathy and Anders Midtgaard\n| founded = 2010<ref name=about/>\n| area_served = [[Ghana]]\n| homepage = {{URL|www.hopinacademy.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Hopin Academy''' is a non-profit educational organization based in [[Tamale, Ghana|Tamale]], Northern Region, [[Ghana]] that is open to anyone 24 hours a day. Hopin Academy provides pragmatic and innovative approaches towards exploring the various fields of entrepreneurship with the aid of technology, thus beating the competition in labour market. It derived its name from its educational philosophy as a school designed for students to \"hop in and hop out,\" rather than having strictly organized timetable structures.<ref name=Hopin>{{Cite web|title = Hopin Academy|url = http://hopinacademy.org/|website = hopinacademy.org|accessdate = 2015-12-03}}</ref> The school specializes on training online marketing, social media communication, writing, video production, entrepreneurial work and web communications.<ref name=Hopin />  Hopin Academy has established an international academic partnership with [[Bryn Mawr College]] and [[Haverford College]]  through the BiCo-Dalun Summer Action Research Fellowship, a learning program fostered in 2010 where Bryn Mawr and Haverford students create community projects with Ghanaian partners.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dalun Community Partners {{!}} Dalun-BiCo Lagim Tehi Tuma|url = http://lagim.blogs.brynmawr.edu/category/dalun-community-partners/|website = lagim.blogs.brynmawr.edu|accessdate = 2015-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Bryn Mawr College: Bryn Mawr / Haverford Education Program|url = http://www.brynmawr.edu/education/fieldwork.html|website = www.brynmawr.edu|accessdate = 2015-12-03|url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160105131000/http://www.brynmawr.edu/education/fieldwork.html|archivedate = 2016-01-05|df = }}</ref> According to the Hopin Academy website, they offer courses in writing, design, film, and entrepreneurial work.<ref name=about>{{Cite web |title = About us - Hopin Academy |url = http://hopinacademy.org/about.html |website = hopinacademy.org |accessdate = 2015-12-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160121002929/http://hopinacademy.org/about.html |archivedate = 2016-01-21 |df =  }}</ref> They also provide training to NGOs, government organizations, and other schools, such as the Olive School of Journalism and they as well provide entrepreneurial support to start up business from idea stages through to implementations and also provide financial support to many startups.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Olive Students to be Trained in Web Design and Social Media|url = http://www.osjournalism.com/olive-students-to-be-trained-in-web-design-and-social-media/|website = www.osjournalism.com|accessdate = 2015-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Olive School Of Journalism : News And Events|url = http://olivestudents.blogspot.com/p/news-and-events.html|website = olivestudents.blogspot.com|accessdate = 2015-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nHopin Academy was started in 2010 as a social enterprise that aims to serve as an alternative to the Ghanaian public education system.<ref>{{Cite web|title = 10 Under 35 Changemakers in Ghana You Need to Know.|url = https://emeritusky.wordpress.com/2013/12/16/10-under-35-changemakers-in-ghana-you-need-to-know/|website = emeritusky|accessdate = 2015-12-06}}</ref>  The educational initiative was co-founded by a Ghanaian entrepreneur,  MacCarthy M. Mac-Gbathy and the Danish film maker and Harvard-trained \"innovator,\" [[Anders Midtgaard]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Future Awards Africa 2015 Nominees Profiles - Page 3 of 9 - The Future Awards Africa|url = http://thefutureafrica.com/awards/tfaa-2015-nominees-profiles/3/|website = The Future Awards Africa|accessdate = 2015-12-03|language = en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = 10 Under 35 Changemakers in Ghana You Need to Know.|url = https://emeritusky.wordpress.com/2013/12/16/10-under-35-changemakers-in-ghana-you-need-to-know/|website = emeritusky|accessdate = 2015-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Meet the FoDB Team {{!}} Dizem Bella|url = http://www.dizembella.org/content/meet-fodb-team|website = www.dizembella.org|accessdate = 2015-12-03|url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151210195852/http://www.dizembella.org/content/meet-fodb-team|archivedate = 2015-12-10|df = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = 10 Under 35. Changemakers In Ghana - TheNewAfrica|url = http://www.thenewafrica.info/10-changemakers-35/|website = TheNewAfrica|accessdate = 2015-12-06|language = en-US|url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151208232224/http://www.thenewafrica.info/10-changemakers-35/|archivedate = 2015-12-08|df = }}</ref>\n\n==Collaborations==\nIn addition to offering courses and technological resources, Hopin Academy supports Barcamp Tamale, which is a networking forum hosted in Tamale that connects Ghanaian leaders and innovators with young people.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Barcamp Tamale  2015 Comes Off August 15th|url = https://www.modernghana.com/news/636409/1/barcamp-tamale-2015-comes-off-august-15th.html|website = Modern Ghana |accessdate = 2015-12-03|language = en-GB}}</ref> Hopin Academy also supports the Youth Speak Up Project, which is a Ghanaian advocacy program that aims to empower youth through technology education.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Youth Speak Up Project {{!}} Youth Empowerment for Life|url = http://www.yefl-ghana.org/news/youth-speak-up-project|website = www.yefl-ghana.org|accessdate = 2015-12-06|url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151210222656/http://www.yefl-ghana.org/news/youth-speak-up-project|archivedate = 2015-12-10|df = }}</ref> Hopin Academy has collaborated with other educational institutions in the international community, including:\n* [[Young Engineers / Future Leaders|YEfL]]-Ghana\n* Olive School of Journalism\n* [[Tamale Polytechnic]]\n* University for Development Studies\n* [[Bryn Mawr College]]\n* [[Haverford College]]\n*[[Viborg, Denmark|Viborg]] Gymnasium\n* Ghana Friendship Groups\n* [[Copenhagen Business Academy]]<ref name=Hopin />\n*[[Open Foundation West Africa]] (OFWA)\n*NORSAAC\n\n==Projects and operation==\nApart from the entrepreneurial training and business incubation, the center also runs its own business startups in areas such as transportation, agriculture and recycling. They include Agri Transportas, M&M Xpress and Right Shea.\n\nMost recent activity was the Social Media Week (SMW) in December 2019, with various sessions in skills development such as E-Waste up-cycling and monetizing YouTube as well as engagement with some NGOs and traditional authorities.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.hopinacademy.org/}}\n*[https://www.topgradetutoring.co.uk/ Top Grade Tutoring]\n\n[[Category:Schools in Ghana]]\n[[Category:Education companies of Ghana]]\n[[Category:2010 establishments in Ghana]]\n[[Category:Northern Region (Ghana)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Hopin Academy \n| type = for-profit [[private company]]\n| genre = private educational organization in the developing world\n| founders = MacCarthy M. Mac-Gbathy and Anders Midtgaard\n| founded = 2010<ref name=about/>\n| area_served = [[Ghana]]\n| homepage = {{URL|www.hopinacademy.org}}\n}}\n\n'''Hopin Academy''' is a non-profit educational organization based in [[Tamale, Ghana|Tamale]], Northern Region, [[Ghana]] that is open to anyone 24 hours a day. Hopin Academy derived its name from its educational philosophy as a school designed for students to \"hop in and hop out,\" rather than having strictly organized timetable structures.<ref name=Hopin>{{Cite web|title = Hopin Academy|url = http://hopinacademy.org/|website = hopinacademy.org|accessdate = 2015-12-03}}</ref> The school specializes on training online marketing, social media communication, writing, video production, entrepreneurial work and web communications.<ref name=Hopin />  Hopin Academy has established an international academic partnership with [[Bryn Mawr College]] and [[Haverford College]]  through the BiCo-Dalun Summer Action Research Fellowship, a learning program fostered in 2010 where Bryn Mawr and Haverford students create community projects with Ghanaian partners.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dalun Community Partners {{!}} Dalun-BiCo Lagim Tehi Tuma|url = http://lagim.blogs.brynmawr.edu/category/dalun-community-partners/|website = lagim.blogs.brynmawr.edu|accessdate = 2015-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Bryn Mawr College: Bryn Mawr / Haverford Education Program|url = http://www.brynmawr.edu/education/fieldwork.html|website = www.brynmawr.edu|accessdate = 2015-12-03|url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160105131000/http://www.brynmawr.edu/education/fieldwork.html|archivedate = 2016-01-05|df = }}</ref> According to the Hopin Academy website, they offer courses in writing, design, film, and entrepreneurial work.<ref name=about>{{Cite web |title = About us - Hopin Academy |url = http://hopinacademy.org/about.html |website = hopinacademy.org |accessdate = 2015-12-03 |url-status=dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160121002929/http://hopinacademy.org/about.html |archivedate = 2016-01-21 |df =  }}</ref> They also provide training to NGOs, government organizations, and other schools, such as the Olive School of Journalism and they as well provide entrepreneurial support to start up business from idea stages through to implementations and also provide financial support to many startups.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Olive Students to be Trained in Web Design and Social Media|url = http://www.osjournalism.com/olive-students-to-be-trained-in-web-design-and-social-media/|website = www.osjournalism.com|accessdate = 2015-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Olive School Of Journalism : News And Events|url = http://olivestudents.blogspot.com/p/news-and-events.html|website = olivestudents.blogspot.com|accessdate = 2015-12-03}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nHopin Academy was started in 2010 as a social enterprise that aims to serve as an alternative to the Ghanaian public education system.<ref>{{Cite web|title = 10 Under 35 Changemakers in Ghana You Need to Know.|url = https://emeritusky.wordpress.com/2013/12/16/10-under-35-changemakers-in-ghana-you-need-to-know/|website = emeritusky|accessdate = 2015-12-06}}</ref>  The educational initiative was co-founded by a Ghanaian entrepreneur,  MacCarthy M. Mac-Gbathy and the Danish film maker and Harvard-trained \"innovator,\" [[Anders Midtgaard]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Future Awards Africa 2015 Nominees Profiles - Page 3 of 9 - The Future Awards Africa|url = http://thefutureafrica.com/awards/tfaa-2015-nominees-profiles/3/|website = The Future Awards Africa|accessdate = 2015-12-03|language = en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = 10 Under 35 Changemakers in Ghana You Need to Know.|url = https://emeritusky.wordpress.com/2013/12/16/10-under-35-changemakers-in-ghana-you-need-to-know/|website = emeritusky|accessdate = 2015-12-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Meet the FoDB Team {{!}} Dizem Bella|url = http://www.dizembella.org/content/meet-fodb-team|website = www.dizembella.org|accessdate = 2015-12-03|url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20151210195852/http://www.dizembella.org/content/meet-fodb-team|archivedate = 2015-12-10|df = }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = 10 Under 35. Changemakers In Ghana - TheNewAfrica|url = http://www.thenewafrica.info/10-changemakers-35/|website = TheNewAfrica|accessdate = 2015-12-06|language = en-US|url-status=dead|archiveurl = https://web.